ainst the new realities of the capitalist market society. She finds that women responded to the transition to capitalism by upholding a set of values which point toward the creation of a provincial bourgeoisie.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aMiddle classzNew EnglandxHistory. 0aRural womenxEconomic aspectszNew EnglandxHistory. 0aRural womenxEconomic aspectszNew England. 0aRural womenzNew EnglandxHistory. 0aRural womenzNew EnglandxSocial life and customs. 0aRural womenzNew EnglandxSociological aspects. 0aWomenzNew EnglandxHistory. 4aGender Studies. 4aU.S. History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173149540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501731495423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501731495/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles